        <section id="introduction" >
            <h2>Introduction</h2>
            <p>Renewable energy resources are naturally replenished sources of energy such as sunlight, wind, and water. Unlike fossil fuels, they do not deplete over time and have less impact on the environment. These energy sources are key to creating a sustainable and eco-friendly energy system.</p>
        </section>
    
</section>

        <!-- Types of Renewable Energy -->
        <section id="types">
            <h2>Types of Renewable Energy</h2>

            <!-- Solar Energy -->
            <section id="solar">
                <h3>Solar Energy</h3>
                <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcTQLeEVZdr6szmMJv5EU_1SY7w6e5WeV0wSZQ&s">
                <p>Solar energy is captured from sunlight and converted into electricity using solar panels.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Benefits:</strong> Clean, abundant, reduces electricity bills.</li>
                    <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Residential solar panels, solar farms, solar-powered devices.</li>
                    <li><strong>Challenges:</strong> Weather dependency, high initial cost, requires large space for panels.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Wind Energy -->
            <section id="wind">
                <h3>Wind Energy</h3>
                
                <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQSgrWf5H2Lz6F6j46Msg32InUJqqZNR2NSXw&s">
                <p>Wind energy is generated by converting the kinetic energy of wind into mechanical power or electricity through wind turbines.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Benefits:</strong> No emissions, reduces reliance on fossil fuels, cost-effective in windy areas.</li>
                    <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Wind farms, offshore wind turbines, small wind systems for homes.</li>
                    <li><strong>Challenges:</strong> Noise, visual impact, not suitable everywhere, impacts on wildlife.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Hydropower -->
            <section id="hydro">
                <h3>Hydropower</h3>
                <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcRdiAG80LcTVF26B8Am_9FrRgZqayut0OoUhg&s">
                <p>Hydropower uses the energy of moving water, usually from rivers or dams, to generate electricity.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Benefits:</strong> Reliable, low emissions, can store energy for later use.</li>
                    <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Dams, pumped storage, river hydropower plants.</li>
                    <li><strong>Challenges:</strong> Affects aquatic ecosystems, expensive to build, limited to areas with water sources.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Geothermal Energy -->
            <section id="geothermal">
                
                <h3>Geothermal Energy</h3>
                <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSv83ZSLvISdkELhL8C8-AKBZHBNBVi2n_3zA&s">
                <p>Geothermal energy harnesses heat from the Earthâ€™s core to produce electricity and heat buildings.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Benefits:</strong> Consistent energy supply, small land footprint, low emissions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Geothermal power plants, heating systems for homes and buildings.</li>
                    <li><strong>Challenges:</strong> Limited to specific geographical areas, high upfront costs, possible depletion of geothermal sources.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Biomass Energy -->
            <section id="bio">
                <h3>Biomass Energy</h3>
                <img src="https://powerzone.clarkpublicutilities.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/CPUD22_Biomass-Cycle-1-scaled.jpg" width="320px">
                <p>Biomass energy is generated from organic materials like wood, agricultural crops, and waste.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Benefits:</strong> Reduces waste, carbon-neutral if managed sustainably, can generate electricity and heat.</li>
                    <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Power plants, biofuels for transportation, heating systems.</li>
                    <li><strong>Challenges:</strong> Requires large land for biomass crops, potential deforestation, emits greenhouse gases if not managed properly.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>          
        </section> 
        <section id="materials-methods">
            <h2>Materials or Methods for Types of Renewable Energy</h2>
        
            <section id="solar-materials" class="energy-section">
                <div class="icon">&#9728;</div> <!-- Sun icon for Solar Energy -->
                <h3>Solar Energy</h3>
                <p>Solar energy is harnessed using photovoltaic (PV) cells or solar thermal systems. The main materials used are silicon-based solar cells, glass, and metal frames. Solar panels are installed in areas with high sunlight exposure to capture maximum energy.</p>
            </section>
        
            <section id="wind-materials" class="energy-section">
                <div class="icon">&#127788;</div> <!-- Wind icon -->
                <h3>Wind Energy</h3>
                <p>Wind turbines are made of strong materials like steel, fiberglass, and concrete to withstand high wind speeds. They use large blades connected to a rotor that turns a generator, converting wind into electricity.</p>
            </section>
        
            <section id="hydro-materials" class="energy-section">
                <div class="icon">&#128167;</div> <!-- Water icon -->
                <h3>Hydropower</h3>
                <p>Hydropower plants require large dams or rivers to channel water. The materials used include reinforced concrete for dams and metals like steel for turbines. The force of flowing water spins the turbine, generating electricity.</p>
            </section>
        
            <section id="geothermal-materials" class="energy-section">
                <div class="icon">&#128293;</div> <!-- Fire icon for heat -->
                <h3>Geothermal Energy</h3>
                <p>Geothermal plants use deep drilling techniques and pipes made of heat-resistant materials like steel. Wells are drilled into hot rock formations to extract heat, which is used to produce steam and drive turbines.</p>
            </section>
        
            <section id="bio-materials" class="energy-section">
                <div class="icon">&#127793;</div> <!-- Leaf icon for Biomass -->
                <h3>Biomass Energy</h3>
                <p>Biomass energy systems use organic materials such as wood, agricultural waste, and other biological waste. These materials are burned or decomposed to release energy. Systems often include biomass boilers, anaerobic digesters, and biofuel processing units.</p>
            </section>
        </section>
        
        <section id="benefits">
            <h2>Beneficial for Society</h2>
            <img src="https://media.springernature.com/lw1200/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10311-022-01532-8/MediaObjects/10311_2022_1532_Fig2_HTML.png" width="500px">
            <p>Renewable energy resources offer numerous benefits for society. By reducing dependence on fossil fuels, they help to lower greenhouse gas emissions, which mitigates climate change. Additionally, renewable energy technologies create jobs in industries such as manufacturing, installation, and maintenance. This sector promotes energy security, reduces the risk of fuel supply shortages, and helps stabilize energy prices. With renewable energy, countries can move towards a more sustainable, healthier, and more prosperous future for all.</p>
        </section>
        <!-- Beneficial for the Government Section -->
        <section id="beneficial-government">
            <h2>Beneficial for the Government</h2>
            <img src="https://www.ibef.org/uploads/blog/1727767579_ca655cb6baf1e02f42f7.jpg" width="500px" alt="Government Benefits">
            <p>Renewable energy helps governments reduce their dependence on imported fossil fuels, leading to greater energy security and a more stable economy. By promoting renewable energy projects, governments can generate revenue through taxes, create new job opportunities, and reduce the economic impact of fluctuating fuel prices. Furthermore, renewable energy policies can enhance a country's reputation on the global stage by showcasing a commitment to sustainability and climate change mitigation.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="need-sustainable-energy">
            <div class="sustainable-icon">&#127757;</div> <!-- Globe icon for sustainability -->
            <h2>Need for Sustainable Energy</h2>
            <p>As the global population grows and industrial activities increase, our reliance on fossil fuels has led to severe environmental challenges, including air pollution, climate change, and depletion of natural resources. Sustainable energy provides a solution to these issues by offering a clean, renewable alternative that minimizes environmental impact and ensures energy availability for future generations.</p>
            <blockquote>"The future depends on sustainable energy practices that protect our planet and preserve resources for generations to come."</blockquote>
        </section>
        

        <!-- Conclusion Section -->
        <section id="conclusion">
            <h2>Conclusion</h2>
            <p>Renewable energy resources offer a clean, sustainable solution to the global energy crisis. Despite challenges such as high initial costs and location dependency, these resources are essential for reducing environmental impact and providing energy security for the future. Continued investment and innovation in renewable energy technologies will help overcome challenges and promote their widespread adoption.</p>       
        </section>
